 Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English, Scottish, and northern Irish (of Norman origin): habitational name from Sainte-Foy-de-Montgomery and Saint-Germain-de-Montgomery (Calvados). In Ireland this surname was present in the medieval period, died out, and was then reintroduced from Scotland in the 17th century. It has been Gaelicized in Ireland as <b>Mac Iomaire</b> and in Scotland as <b>Mac Gumaraid</b>."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Matilda","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Latinized form of a Germanic personal name derived from <i>maht</i>, <i>meht</i> ‘might’ + <i>hild</i> ‘battle’. This was the name of an early German queen (  895–968 ), wife of  Henry  the Fowler, who was noted for her piety and generosity. It was also the name of the wife of  William  the Conqueror and of the daughter of  Henry I  of England (  see  Maud  ). The name was introduced into England by the Normans, and this Latinized form is the one that normally occurs in medieval records, while the vernacular form <i>Maud</i> was the one in everyday use. <i>Matilda</i> was revived in England as a learned form in the 18th century."],"variants":[{"name":"Mathilda","meanings":["Old German: Mighty battle maid"]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Lady Matilda Montgomery of Aldwark Castle was born about 1176, in Aldwark, Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom. She married Galfrid de Clarell about 1203, in Tickhill, Yorkshire, England. They were the parents of at least 1 son. She died in Tickhill, Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom."},"et":{"about 1176–":"umbes 1176–Surnud","1173–Male":"1173–Surnud","1203–1285":"1203–1285","1176–Female":"1176–Surnud","1203":"1203","1176":"1176","about 1203":"umbes 1203","1285":"1285","1173":"1173","about 1176":"umbes 1176","Aldwark, Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom":"Aldwark, Yorkshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Tickhill, Yorkshire, England":"Tickhill, Yorkshire, England","Tickhill, Y